The patient is otherwise well appearing and well hydrated, with normal mental status and no signs of respiratory distress. There are no signs of mastoiditis, and the patient is otherwise well appearing and well hydrated.

payload.contentString:
An ear infection may start with a cold and affect the middle ear (otitis media). It can hurt a lot. Most ear infections clear up on their own in a couple of days and do not need antibiotics. Also, antibiotics do not work against viruses, which may be the cause of your infection. Regular doses of pain relievers are the best way to reduce your fever and help you feel better.

Follow-up care is a key part of your treatment and safety. Be sure to make and go to all appointments, and call your doctor or nurse advice line if you are having problems. It's also a good idea to know your test results and keep a list of the medicines you take.

How can you care for yourself at home?
Take pain medicines exactly as directed.
If the doctor gave you a prescription medicine for pain, take it as prescribed.
If you are not taking a prescription pain medicine, take an over-the-counter medicine, such as acetaminophen (Tylenol), ibuprofen (Advil, Motrin), or naproxen (Aleve). Read and follow all instructions on the label.
Do not take two or more pain medicines at the same time unless the doctor told you to. Many pain medicines have acetaminophen, which is Tylenol. Too much acetaminophen (Tylenol) can be harmful.
Plan to take a full dose of pain reliever before bedtime. Getting enough sleep will help you get better.
Try a warm, moist face cloth on the ear. It may help relieve pain.
If your doctor prescribed antibiotics, take them as directed. Do not stop taking them just because you feel better. You need to take the full course of antibiotics.
When should you call for help?

Call your doctor or nurse advice line now or seek immediate medical care if:

You have new or increasing ear pain.
You have new or increasing pus or blood draining from your ear.
You have a fever with a stiff neck or a severe headache.
Watch closely for changes in your health, and be sure to contact your doctor or nurse advice line if:

You have new or worse symptoms.
You are not getting better after taking an antibiotic for 2 days.

payload.contentString:
You/your child has a fever that is most likely caused by a virus based on their current symptoms. Fever is the body's way of fighting infection. It will not cause harm to you/your child.

Generally, higher fever will make you/your child look and feel sicker, but higher fever DOES NOT mean that you/your child has a more serious illnessâ€”as long as they are fully vaccinated, have no underlying chronic illness and are behaving normally, there should be no immediate cause for concern.

You can treat fever with ibuprofen (Motrin or Advil) every six hours for acetaminophen (Tylenol) and every four hours as needed. Ibuprofen SHOULD NOT be given to children younger than six months of age. The goal is NOT to make the temperature normal. As long as you reduce the fever just enough to make your child more active and comfortable, that is what we would like you to achieve.
If you have questions about how much medication to give your child, please ask your medical provider.

It is important to encourage liquid intake. The best time to try to hydrate is one hour after Motrin or Tylenol, when the fever is reduced and the child feels better.

Since your/your child's symptoms are likely caused by a virus, antibiotics are not needed at this time. Keep in mind that along the course of a viral illness, bacterial infections can develop (including ear infections, pneumonia, and sinusitis), so see your doctor or return for worsening/persistent symptoms or concerning new symptoms.

Warning signs that require immediate recheck by a medical provider:
-If your child takes a sudden turn for the worse,
-Fever of 100.4 F), (38 C), for >4 to 5 days, or fever >106 degreesF
-Refusing to drink, no tears when crying; 'sunken" eyes or dry mouth; reduced diapers/urinating.
-Inconsolable, severe headache, confusion, or severe sleepiness.
-Fast breathing, trouble breathing, or using extra chest muscles to breathe.
-Persistent vomiting.
-Neck pain and/or Bye.
-Cool hands/feet.
-New rash.

payload.contentString:
You/your child most likely has a stomach virus based on their current symptoms. Stomach viruses can cause vomiting and/or diarrhea.

The best treatment for this is to make sure your child is drinking appropriate amounts of liquids. Pedialyte or Gatorade is preferred as they contain sugar and salt. Ice pops/popsicles are also an excellent option for rehydrating. The best way to give fluids is in small amounts frequently (not more than 1 ounce every 10 minutes). Try to avoid milk or very sugary juices for several days as they can worsen diarrhea. As long as your child is drinking fluids well, you don't need to worry if they are not eating solid foods over the next couple of days. If it seems like they are getting better, you can then slowly introduce basic foods (BRAT diet - bananas, rice, apples, toast).
You can use acetaminophen (Tylenol) or ibuprofen (Motrin or Advil) as needed for pain/fever. Children under the age of 6 months should not be given ibuprofen. Please ask your provider if you have questions about the right dose for your child. The best time to try to hydrate is 1 hour after Tylenol/Motrin, when the fever is low and thechild feels better.
Your child's symptoms are probably caused by a virus, so antibiotics are not needed at this time. Keep in mind that along the course of a viral illness, bacterial infections can develop so see your doctor or return for worsening/persistent symptoms or concerning new symptoms.

Warning signs that require immediate recheck by a medical provider:
* If your child takes a sudden turn for the worse
* Fever of 100.4F (38C) for > 4-5 days, or fever >106F
* Refusing to drink, no tears when crying; sunken eyes or dry mouth; reduced diapers/urinating
* Persistent vomiting, bloody stools, severe/worsening abdominal pain/right lower abdominal pain,
* Inconsolable, severe headache, confusion, or severe sleepiness
* Fast breathing, trouble breathing, or using extra chest muscles to breathe
* Neck pain and/or stiffness
* Cool hands/feet
* New rash

payload.contentString:
You/your child has been diagnosed with a bacterial sinus infection. This is usually accompanied by these
symptoms: facial pain/discomfort, yellow/green nasal discharge, new onset fever, or worsening upper
respiratory infection symptoms.

As discussed, we will treat with antibiotics. Give the medication as directed.

* It is important to use other medications for pain relief: ibuprofen every 6 hours as needed, nasal saline
spray/drops, and/or decongestants or nasal sprays for older children
* You may use steroid nasal sprays like Flonase or Nasonex once a day for up to 2 weeks. Use a cool mist
humidifier and steam from the shower to help with congestion.

Follow up with the pediatrician or return if symptoms are not improved in 2-3 days or sooner as needed.

Warning signs that require immediate recheck by a medical provider:
* If your child takes a sudden turn for the worse
* Fever of 100.4F (38C) for > 4-5 days, or fever >106F
* Dizziness, severe headache, confusion, persistent lightheadedness or severe sleepiness
* Fast breathing, trouble breathing, or using extra chest muscles to breathe
* Persistent vomiting
* Neck pain and/or stiffness
* Cool hands/feet
* New rash

payload.contentString:
Your child has a cut to the scalp that required staples. We do not see any signs of a concerning brain injury at this time. 
Keep area dry for 24 hours, and then gently rinse 1-2 times daily with warm soap and water every day until the staples are removed. Pat the wound dry; do not rub. Apply Bacitracin 2-3 times daily until staples are removed.
You can keep the wound covered when your child is awake and active.
Return here or your pediatrician for removal of staples in 7-10 days.

Warning signs that require IMMEDIATE recheck by a medical provider:
* Signs of infection: redness or red streaks spreading from the wound, drainage or discharge, swelling, fever, increasing pain
* Wound opening
* Any sudden worsening of symptoms, such as severe headache
* Unusual behavior such as confusion, inconsolable crying or excessive sleepiness
* Vomiting
* Staggering/loss of balance, weakness of arms/legs, or seizure
* Neck pain, neck stiffness
